These concilia plebis could only be convened by a tribune, or aedile, and the auspices were not taken before they met, as in the case of the comitia. The resolutions passed in them, called plebiscita, were long regarded as informal de- clarations of the will of a single order of the state, and as such were never sanctioned by the patrum auctoritas, though the Hortensian law of n.c. 288 gave them binding force, and thus raised them to the level of the loyes passed in the comitia. Cf. Mommsen, Ro'mische Forsch. 177.
